Soft & thick peanut butter blossoms! 🍪🍪 Have you tried the recipe from my site before? My trick is to press the kiss candy in while the cookies are warm, and then immediately put them in the freezer to help them set quickly. You can roll in granulated sugar or colored sugar sprinkles. 💗 You could also use a peanut butter cup instead of a Hershey’s Kisses candy. 😍😍 Grab these ingredients and find the full recipe on my website and linked in my bio now @sallysbakeblog

1/2 teaspoon baking soda
1/4 teaspoon salt

These are Oreo balls! Have you ever made this popular treat before? It’s so easy. 😆 Grind 36 whole Oreos (1 standard package) into crumbs, then mix with 1 8-ounce block full fat and softened cream cheese. Roll into 28-32 1 Tablespoon size balls, refrigerate to set, and then coat with chocolate. 🍫🍫 This is my handy spiral dipping tool, and I got it off Amazon. I link to it in the post if you ever want one of these nifty little things. 🙃🙃 A fork and toothpick work too! Tap the truffle on the side of the bowl to rid excess chocolate. Decorate with sprinkles, Oreo crumbs, drizzles of chocolate, etc! 💜 You can use Golden oreos, or other flavors too (love them with mint Oreos). All of my troubleshooting tips and the full recipe on my site, linked in my bio now @sallysbakeblog

https://sallysbakingaddiction.com/oreo-balls-recipe/

Peppermint bark is a SNAP to make 🤪🤪 with just 5 ingredients. Have you tried it before? This simple recipe for the classic Christmas treat features 3 layers of white and dark chocolates flavored with peppermint extract, plus crushed candy canes for garnish. (The candy canes get a bit chewy, so they aren’t break-your-teeth hard.) The bark sets in an hour and disappears even quicker. 😂 It’s all really simple, but I have several success tips included in the full printable recipe on my website, linked in my bio now @sallysbakeblog 🎁💚 

I usually use Ghirardelli or Baker’s brand chocolate bars found in the baking aisle. You can spread it all out on a lined baking sheet (instead of a square pan) if desired. Grab these ingredients:

-12 ounces (339g) white chocolate, divided (I don’t recommend white chocolate morsels)
-6 ounces (170g) semi-sweet chocolate (I don’t recommend chocolate chips)
-1 and 1/2 teaspoons vegetable oil or coconut oil, divided (helps smooth out the chocolate)
-1/2 teaspoon peppermint extract, divided
-2-3 regular size candy canes (24-36g total), crushed

Vanilla buttercream! 😉😉🤪🤪 This is American vanilla buttercream, no frills, just a sweet crown for your cakes, cupcakes, and confections. 🧁🎂👑 I have the full recipe and longer video tutorial on my website. You don’t need much... just butter, confectioners’ sugar, vanilla, heavy cream or milk (I prefer heavy cream, room temp), and salt. My best buttercream tip: Over-whipping vanilla buttercream creates air bubbles. 🫧 The taste is no different, but the buttercream is no longer smooth and velvet-y. 😕 Here’s how to get rid of air bubbles in your frosting: Ditch the mixer. Grab a spoon or spatula and begin stirring the buttercream by hand. Mash the frosting up against the side of the bowl to “pop” the bubbles. ✨ Do this until most of the air bubbles pop, about 1-2 minutes. This trick requires a lot of arm muscle! A workout. Wink wink. 😂

GUINNESS CAKE! 🍰 You don’t have to like beer to love this one. 💚💚 Dark, smooth, and creamy, with roast coffee and caramel undertones, Guinness stout is often used in baking and almost always paired with chocolate. 🍻 The two work well together because Guinness, like coffee, intensifies chocolate’s natural flavor. 🍀✨ It doesn't taste like beer, just a more complex chocolate with a malty background. Many recipes don't call for this, but I swear by it: reduce the Guinness down on the stove before using. You won't regret that deeper flavor! 🤩🤩🤩
